entry.title: Optimize several things about DOM Parts [2/2]
entry.content:
This CL continues the optimization work, with these changes:

- Replace ClonePartsFrom() with PartRoot::CloneParts(), to centralize

the part cloning functionality into a single place.

- Replace NodeCloningData's HeapHashMap architecture with a much

simpler stack architecture. Also eliminate the cloning part queue,

and replace it with a clone-as-you-go approach. With this new

system, as a Node containing Parts is cloned, the Parts are

iterated and cloned, validating them with IsValid first. As

ChildNodeParts are encountered, they are cloned with both sibling

nodes pointing to the same node, and the new ChildNodePart is pushed

onto the part root stack. As the next_sibling is encountered, the

ChildNodePart is updated to have the correct sibling node, and the

part root stack is popped. All of this together achieves the same

behavior, but with much lower speed cost.

- Part::IsValid() is cached to improve speed, and disconnected_

becomes connected_ to avoid a `!`.

- PartRoot's cached parts list is converted from a Deque to a

HeapVector, which is more efficient. That eliminates the ability

to modify the front of the list, so this will adversely impact

performance for some operations when DOMPartsAPIActivePartTracking

is enabled (off by default).

entry.title: Fix CRD host crash in ipcz::APIObjectImpl<ipcz::Router,1>::FromObject
entry.content:
We started seeing this crash in M118 after switching to MojoIpcz. After

digging in, it appears that this problem has been around for several

years but the previous Mojo impl did not crash deterministically.



The issue is that our Daemon process creates an IpcChannelProxy server

and then attempts to launch an elevated child process. If the child

process launch fails, a method called ReportFatalError() is called

which in turn calls CloseChannel(). CloseChannel() checks whether

|channel_| has been initialized and short-circuits if so. The problem

is that a channel is open in a temp variable so cleanup isn't handled

correctly until after the temp var has been moved to |channel_|.



The fix is simple as we can just assign directly to |channel_| before

launching the child process.

entry.title: pip-pinch: Fix frozen ARC-R PiP
entry.content:
PiP for ARC-R could not be moved with touch gestures. This was caused

by the client calling `AttemptToStartDrag()` after `ET_GESTURE_BEGIN`

but before `ET_GESTURE_[SCROLL|PINCH]_BEGIN`, during which time the

`gesure_target_` was not yet set.



This regression was the result of crrev/c/4821150 which stopped using

`ET_GESTURE_BEGIN` and instead started using

`ET_GESTURE_[SCROLL|PINCH]_BEGIN` to update the `gesture_target_`. This

works fine with ARC-T but breaks PiP windows in ARC-R.



This commit introduces changes that allows `gesture_target_` to be set

immediately after `ET_GESTURE_START` so that this bug is fixed.



Bug: b/302252882

Test: Manually verified that PiP window moves with touch drag or pinch

both in ARC-R and ARC-T

entry.content:
When processing css_properties.json5, aliases go though a special

"expansion" which sets up the right enum value names, etc.

This expansion produces a list of "updated" aliases, and any existing

references to the non-updated aliases must be "manually" updated

as well. We already did this for aliases that were alternative

properties of *other* aliases (e.g.

-webkit-alternative-animation-with-timeline is an alternative of

-webkit-animation, and both are aliases), however, we neglected to

update any references held to aliases from *non-aliases*. This CL

goes through all properties and makes the necessary updates.



There is no behavior change in this CL, nor any change

to the generated code. It's a preparation to support the work

in Issue 1418401.

entry.title: Make waitForStatus do what it's supposed to do
entry.content:
The expectation for waitForStatus is to block until a certain state is

reached. Confusingly, UrlRequest.StatusListener gets called only once.

This means that waitForStatus would unblock only if we managed to

luckily call UrlRequest#getStatus at the right point in time (i.e. when

it would return the state we're waiting for).



To circumvent that, the listener registered by waitForStatus has to

re-register itself whenever it doesn't receive the expected state.

entry.title: [iOS] Show success snackbar earlier for Save to Photos
entry.content:
This CL changes the SaveToPhotosMediator to present the success snackbar

when the Photos service reports that all the bytes expected to be sent

have actually been sent, rather than when the Photos service calls the

completion callback.



When that happens, the Photos service still needs to perform a request

to add the photo to the user's library, so the Photos app cannot be

opened immediately if the user taps "Open" too early in the snackbar.

If the user does tap "Open" too early, it is recorded in the state of

the mediator. When the service calls the completion callback, that state

is used to determine when the Photos app should be opened then.

entry.title: [file manager] Enable the openFileDialogDriveHostedDoc test
entry.content:
The openFileDialogDriveHostedDoc was disabled long time ago when the

Files App was converted into an SWA. The reason why the test didn't work

was the confusing behavior or the `runSelectFileDialog` test message:

* This message opens a file open dialog, and then

* Waits until a navigation happens in the browser window.



For navigation to happen, the file should be selected in the file open

dialog and the “open” button clicked. This is implemented in javascript

part of the test, but for that it has to send other test messages.



Unfortunately, test messages machinery is not reenterable, so it will

not accept new test messages while it's waiting in handler of an

existing one.



To fix this, this CL splits the `runSelectFileDialog` handler in two:

one opens the dialog and creates a navigation observer, then other

waits for this observer and is supposed to be called only after the test

will do all necessary action.

entry.title: Avoid C++ container re-entrancy in WebBundleParser
entry.content:
In libstdc++ calling std::vector::erase from within object destructor

called by std::vector::clear will result in UAF. See the bug

description for some ASAN logs. What basically happens is:



1. active_parsers_.clear() is called from ~WebBundleParser

2. ~MetadataParser is invoked from the clear method.

3. If complete_callback_ is not null it points to

WebBundleParser::OnParsingComplete which gets invoked.

4. WebBundleParser::OnParsingComplete calls

active_parsrs_.erase(parser) where parser is the MetadataParser

instance already being deleted in step 2.

5. libstdc++ -> UAF, libc++ works fine since in that implementation

clear removes object from internal container storage prior to

invoking the destructor.



Originally I tried to align base::flat_set behavior to work the same

regardless of what standard C++ library (see [1]) is being used, but

apparently chromium project doesn't want to depend on container

re-entrancy in general, hence this fix.



Ref:

[1] https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4908253

entry.title: Speed up paint op serialization.
entry.content:
Paint op serialization can be a bottleneck if there are lots of

canvas ops. Try to reduce the overhead by:



- Inline a bunch of very simple functions (should mostly

be lower than the call overhead).

- Inline a couple of performance-critical functions that are

somewhat larger (Serialize(), SerializeOp()).

- Replace remaining_ by memory_end_, so that we don't have to

spend cycles on maintaining remaining_ (this also makes it

impossible to forget incrementing memory_ without decrementing

remaining_, which should help security).

- Make a new member function WriteMultiple() that writes multiple

values in one go, instead of doing bounds checking and pointer

arithmetic separately for each value.

- Remove a trace point that was costly (we hopefully don't need

to trace serialization for each and every op).

- Make a couple of fast paths for common, simple cases

(e.g., not out of memory, serializing flags with no deep

structures, etc.).



M1 Pinpoint (LTO but no PGO, 95% CI, significant results only):



Canvas Lines [ +7.3%, +7.8%]

Leaves [ +0.5%, +0.9%]

motionmark_ramp_composite [ +0.4%, +1.7%]



M1 Pinpoint with PGO (using the old PGO data, so not trained on

current code):



Canvas Lines [ +4.8%, +5.4%]
